INSERT INTO "use_cases" VALUES (926,'Generative AI Newsroom','Academic','https://generative-ai-newsroom.com/all?topic=generative-ai-use-cases','2026-05-27T10:49:27.577373+00:00','HeyGen AI video tool translating correspondent videos for TikTok/Instagram Reels into Spanish, adapting mouth movements and voice to match translated audio, with native speaker review rather than professional translators','The Economist','United States','2025-11-04','https://generative-ai-newsroom.com/inside-the-new-multilingual-newsrooms-using-genai-for-translation-4c3b17269811',NULL,'Chicago’s La Voz, The Economist’s Español TikTok channel, and BBC News Polska have all benefitted from careful use of translation tools with human oversight.

On the second day of his new job Mark Chonofsky heard about an idea he suspected he could replicate in his newsroom. He had just started as an AI fellow at Chicago Public Media. His first task was to compare notes with the other AI fellows embedded in newsrooms. Mark is one of10 AI fellows funded by the Lenfest Institute, OpenAI, and Microsoft, who are working for two years in newsrooms across the US. At the gathering in Phoenix, Dorrine Mendoza from the American Journalism Project, talked throughtheir experiment with translation. Dorrine shared the example of Puerto Rico’s Centro de Periodismo Investigativo who used their AJP grant to experiment with sensitively translating articles from Spanish to English using GenAI. Mark realised he could flip this and help with translating English articles from theChicago Sun-Timesto Spanish for the Chicago newspaperLa Voz.

Mark had noticed that previously it could be a few days before an English-language article would be published in Spanish in La Voz. “Their previous workflow was: decide on articles after they’re published then translate them the next day, publish them the following day — which meant that the news was always two days old. My dinner party line is ‘that’s not news, it’s olds’,” he joked. In a more serious tone to an audience at the News Product Alliance (NPA) summit in Chicago in October he said: “You can’t publish a breaking news story two days later, no-one wants to hear that.”

He created a tool that automatically downloaded The Sun-Times’ articles and pushed them to the OpenAI API. The prompt he created to translate the articles also included instructions about tone and style, punctuation, and the specific Spanish dialect popularly spoken in Chicago. The tool then pushed the translation to a Google doc for editors to work on. When the editor indicated the article was ready for publication, they could send the story to their CMS with a single click.

Thefirsttwoarticles were published on April, 22 with a sentence at the end: “Traducido por La Voz Chicago con inteligencia artificial (AI)” (Translated for La Voz Chicago with artificial intelligence (AI)). But there was a problem: “We did that for a couple of weeks, monitored that and I realized that a huge obstacle was in images. They’d [the editorial team at La Voz] get an article with five images in it, they weren’t getting any caption translations and [would] have to go through manually and find the images in the CMS and put them in. That was often very time consuming because it wasn’t always easy to find the images that were referenced in the original article.”

“I expanded what we were doing in that Google doc to include some structured text so that it would be possible to always know which image was which.” The “structured text” is text that will always follow the same format and the journalists should not delete or change. Here it includes words like “ — — Image — -”,“Caption:”, “Alt text:”. Mark added a feature in his tool to automatically pull these images through to the CMS.

Once these wrinkles were ironed out, the team at La Voz were ready to react quickly to breaking news. “The landmark article for us was the Pope profile,” Mark told me. This was an important story for their target audience, he told the NPA summit: “A lot of people who care about the Pope are Catholic, a lot of Spanish speakers are Catholic”. Plus, Pope Leo XIV is from Chicago. TheChicago Sun-Times rana profile from the Associate Press of the Pope on May, 8 — the day he was announced as Pope. Crucially,La Voz published the Spanish-language versionon the same day. “It was given that the previous status quo was days, Pope Day was hours,” he said. The team had averted Mark’s so-called “olds” and instead publishedfreshnews. The impact was immense, he told the NPA summit: “immediately we hit five-fold normal traffic”.

La Voz’s use of GenAI is an example where the emphasis is not on fewer human translators but on doing what they couldn’t achieve as quickly before.

Another newsroom that has used GenAI translations in a transformative way is the Economist. In an experiment with translating correspondents’ short videos they used AI video tool HeyGen to translate the videos for TikTok and Instagram Reels. Ludwig Siegele, the Senior Editor for AI Initiatives, explained to me that initially they sent the videos to an external translation company to check. However, he found that the quality of the videos were better when native speakerswithinthe newsroom checked them because their corrections were closer to the natural way people speak than those of translators. “They [translators] tend to go verbatim, so ‘is this the correct word’ not ‘does this sound like somebody would actually speak?’” he said.

Here, you can see Ethan Wu, Asia Business and Finance Editor,speaking in Engl',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
